I tried this code:

```rust
use core::cmp::Ordering;

#[derive(Eq)]
pub struct Data {
    id: u64,
    published: u64,
}

impl PartialEq for Data {

    fn eq(&self, other: &Self) -> bool {
        self.id == other.id
    }

}

impl Ord for Data {

    fn cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> Ordering {
        self.published.cmp(&other.published).then_with(|| self.id.cmp(&other.id))
    }

}

impl PartialOrd for Data {

    fn partial_cmp(&self, other: &Self) -> Option<Ordering> {
        Some(self.cmp(other))
    }

}

#[test]
fn tests() {
    use std::collections::BTreeSet;

    let mut set = BTreeSet::new();
    set.insert(Data { id: 0, published: 0 });
    set.insert(Data { id: 0, published: 1 });

    // Please note: 2
    assert_eq!(set.len(), 2);

    // Now it's only: 1
    assert_eq!(set.into_iter().collect::<BTreeSet<_>>().len(), 1);
}
```

I expected to see this happen: the first `assert_eq!()` shows that the set has 2 items. That should be correct for the second `assert_eq!()` call (which means 2 items).

Instead, this happened: the second `assert_eq!()` passes with just 1 item in the set.

